
TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Psychoanalytic Reading of Hostile Takeover Events
AU  - Schneider, Susan C.
AU  - Dunbar, Roger L. M.
Y1  - 1992/07/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1992.4282002
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1992.4282002
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 537
EP  - 567
VL  - 17
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Hostile takeovers are interorganizational events that threaten organizational identity and integrity. Yet different meanings and different levels of meaning can be revealed by interpreting the texts that describe hostile takeover events. A psychoanalytic reading of these texts provides a way to explore the deeper meanings of these events. In addition, the media coverage of these events demonstrates both the reflection and construction of social reality, or ?contemporary? culture. Interpreting the texts of hostile takeover events provides a way to both enrich our understanding of interorganizational phenomena and illuminate important social issues that might otherwise be kept in the dark.
AB  - Hostile takeovers are interorganizational events that threaten organizational identity and integrity. Yet different meanings and different levels of meaning can be revealed by interpreting the texts that describe hostile takeover events. A psychoanalytic reading of these texts provides a way to explore the deeper meanings of these events. In addition, the media coverage of these events demonstrates both the reflection and construction of social reality, or ?contemporary? culture. Interpreting the texts of hostile takeover events provides a way to both enrich our understanding of interorganizational phenomena and illuminate important social issues that might otherwise be kept in the dark.
